\hypertarget{creating-connections}{%
\section{Creating connections}\label{creating-connections}}

\hypertarget{create-a-dsn}{%
\subsection{Create a DSN}\label{create-a-dsn}}

You must create a DSN before you can connect before you can connect to
the database using R.

\hypertarget{usersystem-dsn}{%
\subsubsection{User/System DSN}\label{usersystem-dsn}}

You may configure a User or System DSN on your machine.

\includegraphics{../images/dsn.PNG}

\hypertarget{in-code}{%
\subsubsection{In code}\label{in-code}}

You may define your odbc connection in code, like below.

\textbf{This is probably what you want to do if you're distributing code
to colleagues with access to the same database, but may have named their
User/System DSN something different.}

\emph{Far as I can tell, you can't connect to an MS Access database this
way, you must create a User or System DSN first (see below).}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Configure the connection}
\NormalTok{rov <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{dbConnect}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{odbc}\NormalTok{(), }
                 \DataTypeTok{Driver =} \StringTok{"SQL Server"}\NormalTok{, }
                 \DataTypeTok{Server =} \StringTok{"161.55.235.187"}\NormalTok{, }
                 \DataTypeTok{Database =} \StringTok{"ROV2"}\NormalTok{, }
                 \DataTypeTok{Trusted_Connection =} \StringTok{"True"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Show connection details}
\NormalTok{rov}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <OdbcConnection> dbo@SWC-ESTRELLA-S
##   Database: ROV2
##   Microsoft SQL Server Version: 12.00.5214
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Disconnect from database}
\KeywordTok{dbDisconnect}\NormalTok{(rov)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{explore-the-training-database}{%
\section{Explore the training
database}\label{explore-the-training-database}}

The database \texttt{training.accdb} is the same database used by Don
Pearson's SQL training course at the Santa Cruz laboratory. It is
provided in this Git repository.

\hypertarget{using-ms-access}{%
\subsection{Using MS Access}\label{using-ms-access}}

The database \textbf{training.accdb} contains three main tables with the
following relationships:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{CRUISE}
\item
  \textbf{HAUL} (linked to CRUISE on CRUISE)
\item
  \textbf{FISH} (linked to HAUL on HAUL)
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{using-dbidbconnect}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Using
\texttt{DBI::dbConnect()}}{Using DBI::dbConnect()}}\label{using-dbidbconnect}}

\hypertarget{create-a-connection}{%
\subsubsection{Create a connection}\label{create-a-connection}}

\texttt{DBI::dbConnect()} creates the connection to the database.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Define a connection to the Training database located in the Data dir}
\NormalTok{con <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{dbConnect}\NormalTok{(odbc}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{odbc}\NormalTok{(), }\StringTok{"training"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{timeout =} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{view-tables-in-the-database}{%
\subsubsection{View tables in the
database}\label{view-tables-in-the-database}}

Once a connection has been established, use \texttt{DBI::dbLIstTables()}
to list the tables in the database.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{dbListTables}\NormalTok{(con)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{using-dplyr}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Using
\texttt{dplyr}}{Using dplyr}}\label{using-dplyr}}

You can write your query in \texttt{dplyr} syntax and it will be
translated into SQL code. 😲

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Create query}
\NormalTok{q1 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"CRUISE"}\NormalTok{)  }

\CommentTok{# Show query}
\KeywordTok{show_query}\NormalTok{(q1)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <SQL>
## SELECT *
## FROM `CRUISE`
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{in-an-r-notebook-code-chunk}{%
\subsection{In an R Notebook code
chunk}\label{in-an-r-notebook-code-chunk}}

You can even embed SQL code in an .Rmd chunk. I'm not sure when I'd do
that, but\ldots{} 🤷‍♂

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{SELECT}\NormalTok{ *}
\KeywordTok{FROM}\NormalTok{ (}\OtherTok{"CRUISE"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\CommentTok{# Print the data frame}
\NormalTok{sql.df}

\hypertarget{create-a-pointer-to-a-table}{%
\subsection{Create a pointer to a
table}\label{create-a-pointer-to-a-table}}

The code below creates a pointer to the table \texttt{CRUISE}, rather
than actually pulling the data into memory.

This prevents potentially expensive operations in the event of a large
table or query.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Create a pointer to the cruise table in the database }
\NormalTok{cruise <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"CRUISE"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Print the table}
\NormalTok{cruise}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Who led the most cruises?

\hypertarget{using-dplyr-1}{%

\texttt{dplyr}}{Using dplyr}}\label{using-dplyr-1}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Create the connection}
\NormalTok{cruise <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"CRUISE"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Summarize using dplyr}
\NormalTok{leader.dplyr <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{cruise }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }

\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{tally}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{collect}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{desc}\NormalTok{(n))}

\hypertarget{join-tables}{%
\subsection{Join tables}\label{join-tables}}

Query all rows in \texttt{fish}, add \texttt{HAUL\_NO} and
\texttt{START\_DEPTH\_FATH} from \texttt{haul}, and add
\texttt{CRUISE\_NO} and \texttt{START\_DATE} from \texttt{cruise}.

\hypertarget{using-dplyr-2}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Using
\texttt{dplyr}}{Using dplyr}}\label{using-dplyr-2}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Create database pointers}
\NormalTok{cruise <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"CRUISE"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{haul   <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"HAUL"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{fish   <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"FISH"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Query joined tables}
\NormalTok{fish.dplyr <-}\StringTok{  }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(fish, SPECIES, SEX, FLENGTH, CRUISE_NO, HAUL_NO) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{left_join}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(haul, CRUISE_NO, HAUL_NO, START_DEPTH_FATH)) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{left_join}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(cruise, CRUISE_NO, START_DATE)) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{collect}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}

\hypertarget{plot-some-rov-transects}{%
\subsection{Plot some ROV transects}\label{plot-some-rov-transects}}

The code below won't work unless you have acces to the ROV database. But
I wanted to demonstrate how quickly this extracts a lot of data
(\textasciitilde{}33,000 records) from a very large table (2,415,487
records with 32 attributes), compared to reading the whole table into
memory and then doing operations on it.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# This won't work unless you have access to the ROV database}
\NormalTok{con.rov <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{dbConnect}\NormalTok{(odbc}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{odbc}\NormalTok{(), }\StringTok{"ROV2"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{timeout =} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{nav <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con.rov, }\StringTok{"tbl_NAV"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{logs <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tbl}\NormalTok{(con.rov, }\StringTok{"tbl_LOGS"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Query and plot in one step}
\NormalTok{rov.map <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{nav }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(nav_id}\OperatorTok{:}\NormalTok{date_time,}\DataTypeTok{lat =}\NormalTok{ lat_r, }\DataTypeTok{long =}\NormalTok{ long_r) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{left_join}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(logs, dive_name, survey_number, site_general)) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(survey_number }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{48}\NormalTok{, site_general }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "Tanner Bank"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{    }\KeywordTok{geom_path}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(long,lat,}\DataTypeTok{group =}\NormalTok{ dive_name)) }\OperatorTok{+}
\StringTok{    }\KeywordTok{coord_map}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{theme_bw}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
